[normal]              
[normal]The BBC seems to be getting bigger, 'flabbier', less critical of itself, careless, arrogant
[normal],  and
[normal] outrageously generous to itself with public money. The recent 
[normal]Savil
[normal] scandal suggests the BBC can be sloppy and very evasive.
[normal]There are more TV and Radio cha
[normal]nnels. The more channels there are, the more diluted the quality of the 
[normal]programmes
[normal] becomes. But probably Radio and local radio are doing better than TV.  
[normal]There are excellent 
[normal]programmes
[normal] but fewer of them. Many believe the BBC has been 
[normal]dumbing
[normal] down. (We ha
[normal]d a black and white TV with one channel - The BBC - I was allowed to stay up for 'The Cherry Orchard'. Now there are many channels with no 
[normal]programmes
[normal] like the Cherry Orchard.) It seems everything now has to be 'popular' on all channels.  BBC 4 was planned 
[normal]as an 'Arts Channel'. But the 'arts' 
[normal]programmes
[normal] have been watered down.  What is BBC 3 for? Reduce the hours broadcast and 'distill' the 
[normal]programmes
[normal] into more powerful and potent offerings. 
[normal]Originally, 'heats' were broadcast weekly of 'Young musician of t
[normal]he year'.  Now with more BBC channels, the whole competition is condensed into a couple of 
[normal]programmes
[normal] (with much time given to what the competitors ate for 
[normal]breakfast,
[normal] and the like than their performances). Why?
[normal]The BBC News channel seems to compare badly 
[normal]with Sky News, 
[normal]Algezeera
[normal], France 24, and even CNN. The BBC must have the most extensive news network of any? Building themselves (at public expense) the grandest News studio in the world seems to have resulted in a less concise and less interesting station
[normal].(
[normal]And why waste so much air time every 1/4 hour with the same trailer?)
[normal]Recently on BBC News International, for 12 hours, the main items of International news (every 15 
[normal]mins
[normal]) were the stock market floatation of 
[normal]'Twitter' followed by the activities of the 
[normal]Mayor of Toronto.  
